==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Putative
<hw>Pu"ta*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>putativus</ets>, fr. <ets>putare</ets>, <ets>putatum</ets>, to
reckon, suppose, adjust, prune, cleanse. See <er>Pure</er>, and cf.
<er>Amputate</er>, <er>Compute</er>, <er>Dispute</er>,
<er>Impute</er>.]</ety> <def>Commonly thought or deemed; supposed;
reputed; <as>as, the <ex>putative</ex> father of a child</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧His other <xex>putative</xex> (I dare not say feigned)
friends.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>E. Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus things indifferent, being esteemed useful or pious, became
customary, and then came for reverence into a <qex>putative</qex> and
usurped authority.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Putchuck</ent>⟦br⟧
